04561nam a22006615i 9780292796737DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212005txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927967377 a10.7560/7068802doi  a(DE-B1597)588749  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aE98.C89H65 2005 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.897/073/090412221 aHolm, Tom, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Great Confusion in Indian Affairs :bNative Americans and Whites in the Progressive Era /cTom Holm. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter I. The Vanishing Policy -- tChapter II. Persistent Peoples: Native American Social and Cultural Continuity -- tChapter III. The New Indians -- tChapter IV. Symbols of Native American Resiliency: The Indian Art Movement -- tChapter V. Preserving the “Indian”: The Reassessment of the Native American Image -- tChapter VI. Progressive Ambiguity: The Reassessment of the Vanishing Policy -- tChapter VII. The “Great Confusion” in Indian Affairs -- tChapter VIII. Epilogue: John Collier and Indian Reform -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe United States government thought it could make Indians "vanish." After the Indian Wars ended in the 1880s, the government gave allotments of land to individual Native Americans in order to turn them into farmers and sent their children to boarding schools for indoctrination into the English language, Christianity, and the ways of white people. Federal officials believed that these policies would assimilate Native Americans into white society within a generation or two. But even after decades of governmental efforts to obliterate Indian culture, Native Americans refused to vanish into the mainstream, and tribal identities remained intact. This revisionist history reveals how Native Americans' sense of identity and "peoplehood" helped them resist and eventually defeat the U.S. government's attempts to assimilate them into white society during the Progressive Era (1890s-1920s). Tom Holm discusses how Native Americans, though effectively colonial subjects without political power, nonetheless maintained their group identity through their native languages, religious practices, works of art, and sense of homeland and sacred history. He also describes how Euro-Americans became increasingly fascinated by and supportive of Native American culture, spirituality, and environmental consciousness. In the face of such Native resiliency and non-Native advocacy, the government's assimilation policy became irrelevant and inevitably collapsed. The great confusion in Indian affairs during the Progressive Era, Holm concludes, ultimately paved the way for Native American tribes to be recognized as nations with certain sovereign rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAssimilation (Sociology)zUnited StatesxHistory. 0aIndians in popular culture. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCultural assimilation. 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericaxPolitics and government. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70688040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796737423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796737/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK